---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<BaseLayout title="Tools" description="Practical guides for Eastern Christian life — your first visit, fasting, how to venerate an icon.">

  <div class="article-surface">
    <div class="article-hero">
      <div class="container--narrow" style="position:relative;">
        <div class="breadcrumbs">
          <a href={`${base}/`}>Home</a>
          <span class="sep">›</span>
          <span style="color:var(--censer-smoke)">Tools</span>
        </div>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span class="tag">Practical Guide</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="article-title">Your First Visit to a Byzantine Parish</h1>
        <p class="article-subtitle">Everything you need to know before, during, and after your first Divine Liturgy.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="article-body">
      <div class="container--narrow">

        <p style="margin-bottom:40px;">No preparation required. No dress code. No prerequisite beliefs. But if knowing what to expect helps settle the nerves, keep reading.</p>

        <div class="tool-step">
          <div class="tool-step-num">1</div>
          <div class="tool-step-content">
            <h3>Before You Go</h3>
            <p>Search "Byzantine liturgy" plus your city. Sunday times vary, usually between 9:00 and 11:00 AM. Arrive five to ten minutes early. That's it.</p>
            <div class="sensory-note">
              <strong>What to wear:</strong> Business casual is a safe bet. Some older parishioners may wear head coverings. Visitors are not expected to.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tool-step">
          <div class="tool-step-num">2</div>
          <div class="tool-step-content">
            <h3>When You Walk In</h3>
            <p>Beeswax and incense. That's the first thing. The church will be dimmer than expected. Look for the icon of Christ to the right of the main doors, the Theotokos (Mary) to the left.</p>
            <div class="sensory-note">
              <strong>What you'll see:</strong> A wall of icons (the iconostasis) across the front. Candle stands. Perhaps older parishioners crossing themselves and bowing. The space is alive before the service starts.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tool-step">
          <div class="tool-step-num">3</div>
          <div class="tool-step-content">
            <h3>During the Liturgy</h3>
            <p>Almost everything is sung. The congregation stands for most of the service. Sitting is fine if needed. Most parishes provide handouts with the responses.</p>
            <p>Do not worry about following along perfectly. No one expects that.</p>
            <div class="sensory-note">
              <strong>What you'll hear:</strong> Chanting, sometimes in English, sometimes in a liturgical language. No instruments. Only human voices.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tool-step">
          <div class="tool-step-num">4</div>
          <div class="tool-step-content">
            <h3>Communion</h3>
            <p>Best not to receive on a first visit. Speak with the priest first. But approaching for a blessing is warmly welcomed: cross your arms over your chest and say "a blessing, Father."</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tool-step">
          <div class="tool-step-num">5</div>
          <div class="tool-step-content">
            <h3>After the Liturgy</h3>
            <p>Go to coffee hour. This matters. Eastern Christians are famously hospitable. Someone will hand you a plate of food within five minutes. Possibly sooner.</p>
            <div class="sensory-note">
              <strong>What to expect:</strong> Coffee, conversation, homemade food. If someone asks "is this your first time?" — that's an invitation, not an interrogation.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p>Ready to understand what's happening during the Liturgy?</p>
          <a href={`${base}/journey/`} class="btn-primary">Step 1: What Happens Behind Those Doors?</a>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .tool-step {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 48px 1fr;
    gap: 20px;
    margin-bottom: 32px;
    align-items: start;
  }
  .tool-step-num {
    width: 48px;
    height: 48px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    border: 0.5px solid var(--gold-15);
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 20px;
    color: var(--halo-gold);
    opacity: 0.6;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }
  .tool-step-content h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 19px;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--beeswax);
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .tool-step-content p {
    font-size: 15px;
    color: var(--aged-vellum);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  .sensory-note {
    margin-top: 12px;
    padding: 12px 16px;
    background: var(--gold-04);
    border-radius: 6px;
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--censer-smoke);
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
  .sensory-note strong { color: var(--halo-gold); font-weight: 500; }
  .cta-box {
    margin-top: 48px;
    padding: 24px;
    background: var(--gold-04);
    border-radius: 8px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .cta-box p {
    font-size: 16px;
    color: var(--beeswax);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
</style>
